market_price_verification_meta_recipe
  record_type "meta_recipe"
  topic "market_price_verification"
  title "Market-price verification: catch false numeric price claims in a document"
  summary "Machine-readable recipe for reproducing the deterministic market-price fact check (issue #493) from a data-driven reference registry, the relative-meta-logic evidence machinery, and the document-verification handler. A screenshot that repeats `ETH in 2024: $1,700` across many years and scenarios is not merely opinion: each line asserts a checkable numeric claim about a traded asset's price in a period. The recipe extracts every such claim, grounds each asset in an external Wikidata entity, looks up the recorded daily-candle range for that asset and period from data/seed/market-price-references.lino, and contradicts a claim only when its price falls outside the recorded [min, max] range — weighing the verdict under github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic. It is grounded: tests/unit/specification/market_price_verification_meta_algorithm.rs asserts the live source still matches every step, external grounding, handler function, Rust-JS parity target, data source, and pinning test listed here, so this file always describes how the running code was produced."
  generalization "Any `is this numeric market claim true?` question is produced by the same ordered steps, across the whole class of market-price claims and every supported language (en/ru/hi/zh). To add a new asset or a new period: append an `asset` (with its Wikidata `grounded-in` entity, `quote-currency`, and per-language `lexeme`/`surface` aliases) or a `reference <period>` (with `source-id`, `source-label`, `source-url`, and the observed min/max price and date) to data/seed/market-price-references.lino. The recogniser scans the whole alias registry rather than any single ticker (issue #386: no per-language phrase table in Rust), the range lookup is keyed by asset and period, and relative-meta-logic contradicts a claim only outside the recorded range so a faithful check never over-claims on prices that were actually reached. No asset-specific or year-specific code path is ever added."
step_register_reference_data
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "1"
  id "register_reference_data"
  title "Register verifiable assets and recorded price ranges as seed data"
  detail "data/seed/market-price-references.lino is the single source of truth: one `asset` per traded instrument, carrying a `label`, an external `grounded-in` Wikidata id, a `quote-currency`, per-language `lexeme`/`surface` aliases, and one `reference <period>` per checkable period with `source-id`, `source-label`, `source-url`, `observed-min-price`, `observed-min-date`, `observed-max-price`, and `observed-max-date`. The ranges are the recorded daily-candle extremes from the named first-party source, so the fact check is data, not code — new assets and periods extend the registry without touching the parser."
  seed_file "data/seed/market-price-references.lino"
step_ground_each_asset
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "2"
  id "ground_each_asset"
  title "Ground each asset in an external entity"
  detail "Every `asset` names a `grounded-in` Wikidata entity (Ethereum Q16783523, Bitcoin Q131723) cached under data/cache/wikidata/entity, so the asset an alias refers to has an external, language-independent meaning rather than a bare ticker string. Recognising `эфириум`, `以太坊`, `etherium`, or `$ETH` all resolve to the same grounded asset."
  seed_file "data/seed/market-price-references.lino"
step_recognise_assets_by_alias
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "3"
  id "recognise_assets_by_alias"
  title "Recognise assets by alias across languages, not a phrase table"
  detail "asset_positions scans a line for every alias of every asset in the registry — ASCII aliases matched case-insensitively on word boundaries, non-ASCII aliases matched as substrings — and returns the sorted, de-duplicated match offsets. Because the aliases live in the seed lexicon (issue #386 convention), the recogniser generalises across the whole asset class in every supported language with no hardcoded per-language list in Rust."
  seed_file "src/statement_verification.rs"
step_split_per_asset
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "4"
  id "split_per_asset"
  title "Split each line into one fragment per named asset"
  detail "market_price_fragments uses asset_positions to cut a single line into one fragment per asset it names, so `ETH in 2024: $1,700 BTC in 2024: $40,000` yields one claim for ETH and one for BTC. The splitter is driven by the whole alias registry, never a single ticker."
  seed_file "src/statement_verification.rs"
step_parse_period_and_price
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "5"
  id "parse_period_and_price"
  title "Parse the claimed period and numeric price from each fragment"
  detail "parse_market_price_claim finds the asset alias, a four-digit period year, and a currency-marked amount in the same fragment, skipping the ticker's own `$` marker before reading the price. The result is a structured MarketPriceClaim{asset, period, claimed_price} independent of the surface wording, so the same parser handles every phrasing in every language."
  seed_file "src/statement_verification.rs"
step_weigh_against_recorded_range
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "6"
  id "weigh_against_recorded_range"
  title "Weigh each claim against the recorded range under relative-meta-logic"
  detail "assess_market_price_claim looks up the reference for the claim's asset and period, then marks the claim `contradicted` only when the claimed price is below observed-min-price or above observed-max-price, and `within_recorded_range` otherwise. It feeds a RelativeEvidence at SourceTier::OriginalFirstParty (mass 0.95, Stance::Contradicts or Stance::Supports) into StatementAssessment::assess, which starts the statement at the assumed-true prior and moves it only under that first-party evidence. A price that was actually reached in the period is never flagged, so the check does not over-claim."
  seed_file "src/relative_meta_logic.rs"
step_splice_verdict
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "7"
  id "splice_verdict"
  title "Splice the grounded verdict onto the evidence trace"
  detail "try_document_originality_check calls extract_market_price_claims and assess_market_price_claims over the OCR/text sample and appends market_price_claim:claim_count, per-claim market_price_claim:asset/period/claimed_price/source/range links, and a market_price_claim:assessment payload naming the status, source, recorded range, and posterior for each claim — so the trace states exactly why a numeric claim was caught or accepted."
  seed_file "src/solver_handlers/document_originality.rs"
step_mirror_worker
  record_type "meta_step"
  order "8"
  id "mirror_worker"
  title "Mirror the whole path in the JS worker"
  detail "Reproduce each Rust function as a JS function in the src/web/worker modules so the WASM/browser surface stays in parity (R15): parseMarketPriceReferences/marketPriceReferences load the same seed registry, assetPositions/marketPriceFragments/extractMarketPriceClaims/assessMarketPriceClaims mirror the Rust chain, and the worker emits the same market_price_claim:* evidence markers and the same summary sentence as the Rust handler."
  seed_file "src/web/worker/formal_ai_worker_21.js"
